        "import polars as pl\n",
        "import requests\n",
        "import io\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "from lets_plot import *\n",
        "\n",
        "LetsPlot.setup_html(isolated_frame=True)"
      ],
      "id": "a1b19e24",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# I guess the read_json function is a little picky and it likes having the files be a local path. We can use the io package to essentially do the same thing a tempfile does in 350\n",
        "\n",
        "url = \"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/byuidatascience/data4missing/master/data-raw/flights_missing/flights_missing.json\"\n",
        "response = requests.get(url)\n",
        "df = pl.read_json(io.BytesIO(response.content))"
      ],
      "id": "48561e5c",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "At this point the students don't know how to clean the data so we need to avoid anything that would clean it.\n",
        "\n",
        "Ideas:\n"
      ],
      "id": "e0b9ab05"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "df.describe()"
      ],
      "id": "3057adf0",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Idea 1\n",
        "\n",
        "We can try to use the same question about finding the true weather delays, the only issue is that they don't know how to clean the data yet and num_late_aircraft has missing values in the form of -999. We can either choose a different column or just ignore it for now with a clever use of otherwise.\n",
        "\n",
        "The code is in section 2\n",
        "\n",
        "## Idea 2\n",
        "\n",
        "I think it would be a good idea to ahve them make a boxplot for this assignemnt. We can have them do it based off months, or by seasons fairly easily.\n",
        "\n",
        "I have two ideas, we can either have them make a new column with the when().then().otherwise() logic and then plot that in their boxplots, or we can make seasons. Or we can do both so they have to use the conditional statements twice in one question.\n",
        "\n",
        "We need to include something in the reading about pl.lit and how it means we want to use a string and we are not referring to a column.\n",
        "\n",
        "Another idea for this assignment is that instead of having them fill the na values, they have to use filter to avoid them and they realize how annoying inconsistent na values can be >:). "
      ],
      "id": "7f44926d"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "q2 = df.filter(pl.col('month') !=  'n/a').with_columns([\n",
        "    pl.when(pl.col('month').is_in(['January', 'Febuary', 'March']))\n",
        "    .then(pl.lit('Winter'))\n",
        "    .when(pl.col('month').is_in(['April', 'May', 'June']))\n",
        "    .then(pl.lit('Spring'))\n",
        "    .when(pl.col('month').is_in(['July', 'August', 'September']))\n",
        "    .then(pl.lit('Summer'))\n",
        "    .when(pl.col('month').is_in(['October', 'November', 'December']))\n",
        "    .then(pl.lit('Fall'))\n",
        "    .otherwise(pl.lit('Unknown')).alias('season')\n",
        "])\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "q2 = q2.filter(pl.col('num_of_delays_late_aircraft') != -999).with_columns([\n",
        "    ( pl.col('num_of_delays_late_aircraft')*.3 \n",
        "        +pl.col('num_of_delays_weather')\n",
        "        +pl.when(pl.col('month').is_in(['April', 'May', 'June', 'July', 'August'])).then(pl.col('num_of_delays_nas')*.4).otherwise(pl.col('num_of_delays_nas')*.65))\n",
        "    .alias('new_weather')\n",
        "])"
      ],
      "id": "677cb9e8",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "q2.group_by('month').count().to_pandas()\n",
        "# q2.group_by('season').count().to_pandas()"
      ],
      "id": "8fca7356",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "plot = (\n",
        "    ggplot(q2, aes(x='month', y='new_weather'))\n",
        "    +geom_boxplot()\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "plot"
      ],
      "id": "c5bdb068",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
